riends. His woodcuts and engravings were avidly collected and copied across Europe, and they quickly established his reputation as a master. Praised in life and elegized in death by such thinkers as Martin Luther and Erasmus, he served Emperor Maximilian and other leading church and secular princes in the Holy Roman Empire.Although there is a vast specialized literature on the Nuremberg master, The Essential Dürer fills the need for a foundational book that covers the major aspects of his career. The essays included in this book, written by leading scholars from the United States and Germany, provide an accessible, up-to-date examination of Dürer's art and person as well as his posthumous fame. The essays address an array of topics, from separate and detailed studies of his paintings, drawings, printmaking, and sculpture, to broader concerns such as his visits to and interactions with Venice and the Netherlands, his personal relationships, and his relationships with other artists. Collectively these stimulating essays explore the brilliance of Dürer's creativity and the impact he had on his world, exposing him as an artist fully engaged with the tumultuous intellectual and religious challenges of his time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aArchitecture. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aFine Art.  aGarden History.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.1 aAndersson, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawford Luber, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuneo, Pia F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichberger, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcColl, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb